{{Refimprove|date=January 2017}} [[File:Evaporation ponds Kesterson national wildlife refuge.jpg|thumb|Evaporation ponds in the Kesterson National Wildlife Refuge]] The '''Kesterson National Wildlife Refuge''' was an artificial [[wetland]] environment, created using agricultural [[Surface runoff|runoff]] from farmland in [[California]]'s [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]].
The [[irrigation]] water is transported to the valley from sources in the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] via the [[California Aqueduct]]. Minerals from these sources are carried in the water and concentrated by evaporation from aqueducts, canals, and fields. This has resulted in an exceptionally high accumulation of [[selenium]] and other minerals in the wetlands. Wildlife in this region suffered deformities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minerals.cr.usgs.gov/gips/ducklrg.gif |accessdate=February 15, 2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041029064607/http://minerals.cr.usgs.gov/gips/ducklrg.gif |archivedate=October 29, 2004 }}</ref> due to selenium poisoning, drawing the attention of news media and leading to the closure of the refuge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minerals.cr.usgs.gov/gips/0elemap.htm |accessdate=February 15, 2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310041621/http://minerals.cr.usgs.gov/gips/0elemap.htm |archivedate=March 10, 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tragedy at Kesterson Reservoir: Death of a Wildlife Refuge Illustrates Failings of Water Law|url=http://elr.info/sites/default/files/articles/15.10386.htm|publisher=Environmental Law Reporter|accessdate=12 June 2016|date=1985}}</ref>
[[Kesterson Reservoir]] was a unit of the refuge but is now part of [[San Luis National Wildlife Refuge]].
