[[Image:Eigg.AnSgurr.Canthusus.jpg|thumb|Pitchstone ridge: [[An Sgùrr (Eigg)|An Sgùrr]], [[Eigg]], Scotland]] '''Pitchstone''' is a dull black glassy [[volcanic rock]] formed when [[felsic]] [[lava]] or [[magma]] cools quickly. It is similar to [[obsidian]] but is defined by the [[International Union of Geological Sciences]] as having a higher water content.<ref name=ballin /> It is a volcanic glass; however, unlike a glass, pitchstone has an irregular hackly fracture not a [[conchoidal fracture]]. That is due to its coarser (than obsidian) crystal structure. Pitchstone has a [[resinous]] [[Lustre (mineralogy)|lustre]], or silky in some cases, and a variable composition. Its colour may be mottled, streaked, or uniform brown, red, green, gray, or black. It is an [[extrusive]] rock that is very resistant to [[erosion]].
The pitchstone [[ridge]] of [[An Sgùrr (Eigg)|An Sgùrr]] on the Isle of [[Eigg]], [[Geology of Scotland|Scotland]], was possibly formed as a lava flow in a valley.<ref>{{cite book|last1=al.]|first1=C.H. Emeleus ; contributors: J.D. Hudson ... [et|title=Geology of Rum and the adjacent islands : memoir for 1:50000 geological sheet 60 (Scotland)|date=1997|publisher=Stationery Office|location=London|isbn=0118845179|edition=1. publ.}}</ref>
Pitchstone from the [[Isle of Arran]] was used as the raw material for making various items from the [[Mesolithic]] through the [[Neolithic]] to the [[Early Bronze Age]].<ref name=ballin /> Mesolithic use appears to have been limited to the Isle of Arran itself, while in later periods the material or items made from it were transported around Britain.<ref name=ballin>{{cite journal |last=Ballin |first=Torben Bjarke |date=2015 |title=Arran pitchstone (Scottish volcanic glass): New dating evidence |url= |journal=Journal of Lithic Studies |publisher=[[University of Edinburgh]] |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=5–16 |doi=10.2218/jls.v2i1.1166 }} {{Open access}}</ref>
